# A First `recipe()` — The Ames Housing Data

## The problem

We want to predict `Sale_Price` (already log₁₀-transformed) using four
predictors:

-   `Neighborhood` — qualitative, 29 levels
-   `Gr_Liv_Area` — continuous square footage (right-skewed)
-   `Year_Built` — continuous
-   `Bldg_Type` — qualitative, 5 levels

The equivalent base-R formula would be:

```{r formula-equivalent}
#| eval: false
lm(
  Sale_Price ~ Neighborhood + log10(Gr_Liv_Area) + Year_Built + Bldg_Type,
  data = ames_train
)
```

## Building the recipe

A recipe **specifies** preprocessing steps without immediately executing
them — estimation happens later, during `fit()`.

```{r simple-recipe}
simple_ames <-
  recipe(
    Sale_Price ~ Neighborhood + Gr_Liv_Area + Year_Built + Bldg_Type,
    data = ames_train
  ) %>%
  step_log(Gr_Liv_Area, base = 10) %>% # log-transform living area
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) # dummies for all factor cols

simple_ames
```

::: callout-note
## What just happened?

-   `recipe(..., data = ames_train)` — assigns **roles** (predictor /
    outcome) and inspects column *types*; the data values are not yet
    used.
-   `step_log()` — registers a log transformation to be applied later.
-   `step_dummy()` — registers dummy encoding of all factor/character
    predictors.
-   `all_nominal_predictors()` is a recipe-specific selector — like
    `starts_with()` in dplyr, but role-aware.
:::

## Why recipes beat formulas

| Feature | Base-R formula | `recipes` |
|---------------------------|----------------|-----------------|
| Reuse across multiple models | ✗ | ✓ |
| Handles 100+ dummy columns cleanly | tedious | ✓ (`all_nominal_predictors()`) |
| Prevents data leakage | limited | ✓ (fit-time estimation) |
| Inspect what was learned | ✗ | ✓ (`tidy()`) |
| Extend with custom steps | limited | ✓ |

---

# Using a Recipe Inside a Workflow

Recipes are meant to live inside a `workflow()` — this couples
preprocessing and modeling so that everything is estimated together.

```{r lm-setup}
# Define the model
lm_model <- linear_reg() %>% set_engine("lm")

# Build a workflow — note: only one preprocessor allowed at a time
lm_wflow <-
  workflow() %>%
  add_model(lm_model) %>%
  add_recipe(simple_ames)

lm_wflow
```

## Fit the workflow

`fit()` does two things in sequence: (1) **prepares** the recipe using
`ames_train`, then (2) **fits** the model on the preprocessed training
data.

```{r fit-workflow}
lm_fit <- fit(lm_wflow, ames_train)
lm_fit
```

## Predict on new data

`predict()` automatically applies the *same* preprocessing that was
used at training time — no manual re-transformation needed.

```{r predict-new}
predict(lm_fit, ames_test %>% slice(1:5))
```

## Extract internals

```{r extract-recipe}
# Inspect the trained recipe
lm_fit %>%
  extract_recipe(estimated = TRUE)
```

```{r extract-model}
# Inspect model coefficients (first 8)
lm_fit %>%
  extract_fit_parsnip() %>%
  tidy() %>%
  slice(1:8)
```

::: callout-important
## Data leakage checkpoint

All parameters estimated by a recipe step (means, standard deviations,
PCA loadings, factor levels) are computed **only on training data**. When
`predict()` is called on new data, those stored parameters are re-applied
— not re-estimated. This is a core guarantee of the `recipes` framework.
:::

---

# How Data Flow Through a Recipe

```{r data-flow-diagram}
#| echo: false
#| fig-cap: "Data flow in a tidymodels recipe + workflow"
# A simple text diagram via a styled knitr output
cat(
  "  recipe(formula, data = train)     ← column TYPES inferred here
         │
         ▼
  step_*() chain registered          ← no data used yet
         │
    fit(workflow, train)
         │
         ├─► prep(recipe, train)     ← parameters ESTIMATED on train
         │         log means, dummy levels, PCA weights, etc.
         │
         └─► fit(model, baked_train) ← model fitted on preprocessed train
         
  predict(workflow, new_data)
         │
         ├─► bake(recipe, new_data)  ← stored params APPLIED (not re-estimated)
         └─► predict(model, ...)     ← predictions returned
"
)
```

::: callout-warning
## The golden rule

**Never** pass test or holdout data to `recipe()` or `prep()` for
parameter estimation. The `workflows` package enforces this for you
when you call `fit(workflow, train)` and `predict(workflow, test)`.
:::

