# Important Recipe Steps

## Encoding qualitative variables: `step_dummy()` and friends

### Rare levels with `step_other()`

```{r neighborhood-bar}
#| fig-cap: "Neighborhood frequencies in the Ames training set — note the rare levels"
ames_train %>%
  count(Neighborhood, sort = TRUE) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = reorder(Neighborhood, n))) +
  geom_col(fill = "#3B7DD8", alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_vline(
    xintercept = 0.01 * nrow(ames_train),
    linetype = "dashed",
    colour = "firebrick"
  ) +
  annotate(
    "text",
    x = 0.01 * nrow(ames_train) + 3,
    y = 3,
    label = "1% threshold",
    colour = "firebrick",
    size = 3.2
  ) +
  labs(
    x = "Count",
    y = NULL,
    title = "Neighborhoods with < 1% of training rows will be pooled into 'other'"
  )
```

When rare levels exist, `step_other()` pools them into a single `"other"` category — 
avoiding near-zero-variance dummies that confuse most models.

```{r step-other-recipe}
simple_ames <-
  recipe(
    Sale_Price ~ Neighborhood + Gr_Liv_Area + Year_Built + Bldg_Type,
    data = ames_train
  ) %>%
  step_log(Gr_Liv_Area, base = 10) %>%
  step_other(Neighborhood, threshold = 0.01) %>% # ← pool rare levels
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors())

simple_ames
```

### How dummy variables work

For `Bldg_Type` with five levels, `step_dummy()` creates **four** binary
columns (the first level, `OneFam`, becomes the reference):

| Original | TwoFmCon | Duplex | Twnhs | TwnhsE |
|----------|----------|--------|-------|--------|
| OneFam | 0 | 0 | 0 | 0 |
| TwoFmCon | 1 | 0 | 0 | 0 |
| Duplex | 0 | 1 | 0 | 0 |
| Twnhs | 0 | 0 | 1 | 0 |
| TwnhsE | 0 | 0 | 0 | 1 |

::: callout-note
Use `one_hot = TRUE` inside `step_dummy()` if you need all five
columns (required by some tree-based models and neural networks).
:::

## Interaction terms: `step_interact()`

First, let's visualise whether the relationship between `Gr_Liv_Area`
and `Sale_Price` differs by building type — the classic motivation for
an interaction term.

```{r interaction-plot}
#| fig-cap: "Different slopes by building type suggest an interaction term is warranted"
ggplot(ames_train, aes(x = Gr_Liv_Area, y = 10^Sale_Price)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.15, size = 0.9) +
  facet_wrap(~Bldg_Type, nrow = 1) +
  geom_smooth(method = lm, formula = y ~ x, se = FALSE, colour = "#3B7DD8") +
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10(labels = scales::dollar) +
  labs(
    x = "Gross Living Area (log scale)",
    y = "Sale Price USD (log scale)",
    title = "Slopes differ across building types → add an interaction term"
  )
```

Slopes clearly differ. To capture this in a recipe, we add
`step_interact()` **after** dummies have already been created:

```{r step-interact-recipe}
simple_ames <-
  recipe(
    Sale_Price ~ Neighborhood + Gr_Liv_Area + Year_Built + Bldg_Type,
    data = ames_train
  ) %>%
  step_log(Gr_Liv_Area, base = 10) %>%
  step_other(Neighborhood, threshold = 0.01) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  # Interact log(Gr_Liv_Area) with each Bldg_Type dummy column
  step_interact(~ Gr_Liv_Area:starts_with("Bldg_Type_"))

simple_ames
```

::: callout-important
## Order matters!

`step_interact()` must come **after** `step_dummy()`. Interactions are
formed from the columns as they exist at that point in the recipe chain —
not from the original data.
:::

## Spline functions: `step_ns()`

When a continuous predictor has a **nonlinear** relationship with the
outcome, splines expand that single column into multiple basis columns
that together capture the curve.

```{r spline-plot}
#| fig-cap: "Natural splines with increasing degrees of freedom — 2 underfits, 100 overfits"
plot_smoother <- function(deg_free) {
  ggplot(ames_train, aes(x = Latitude, y = 10^Sale_Price)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.15, size = 0.7) +
    scale_y_log10(labels = scales::dollar) +
    geom_smooth(
      method = lm,
      formula = y ~ ns(x, df = deg_free),
      colour = "#3B7DD8",
      se = FALSE
    ) +
    labs(
      title = paste(deg_free, "spline terms"),
      y = "Sale Price",
      x = "Latitude"
    )
}

(plot_smoother(2) + plot_smoother(5)) /
  (plot_smoother(20) + plot_smoother(100))
```

```{r spline-recipe}
spline_recipe <-
  recipe(
    Sale_Price ~ Neighborhood + Gr_Liv_Area + Year_Built + Bldg_Type + Latitude,
    data = ames_train
  ) %>%
  step_log(Gr_Liv_Area, base = 10) %>%
  step_other(Neighborhood, threshold = 0.01) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  step_interact(~ Gr_Liv_Area:starts_with("Bldg_Type_")) %>%
  step_ns(Latitude, deg_free = 20) # ← natural spline with 20 df

spline_recipe
```

::: callout-tip
The right number of spline terms is a **tuning parameter** (Chapter 12).
Start with 5–20 and let cross-validation guide the choice.
:::

## Feature extraction: `step_pca()`

When several predictors are correlated (e.g., multiple house-size
columns), PCA compresses them into a smaller set of uncorrelated
components.

```{r size-correlation}
#| fig-cap: "Size-related predictors are highly correlated — good PCA candidates"
ames_train %>%
  select(matches("(SF$)|(Gr_Liv)")) %>%
  cor(use = "pairwise.complete.obs") %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  tibble::rownames_to_column("var1") %>%
  tidyr::pivot_longer(-var1, names_to = "var2", values_to = "r") %>%
  ggplot(aes(var1, var2, fill = r)) +
  geom_tile(colour = "white") +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(r, 2)), size = 3) +
  scale_fill_gradient2(
    low = "#D7191C",
    mid = "white",
    high = "#2C7BB6",
    midpoint = 0,
    limits = c(-1, 1)
  ) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 35, hjust = 1)) +
  labs(
    x = NULL,
    y = NULL,
    title = "Correlation matrix of square-footage predictors",
    fill = "r"
  )
```

```{r pca-recipe}
pca_recipe <-
  recipe(
    Sale_Price ~ Neighborhood +
      Gr_Liv_Area +
      Year_Built +
      Bldg_Type +
      Total_Bsmt_SF +
      First_Flr_SF +
      Gr_Liv_Area,
    data = ames_train
  ) %>%
  step_log(Gr_Liv_Area, base = 10) %>%
  step_other(Neighborhood, threshold = 0.01) %>%
  step_normalize(matches("(SF$)|(Gr_Liv)")) %>% # PCA requires same scale
  step_pca(matches("(SF$)|(Gr_Liv)"), num_comp = 2) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors())

pca_recipe
```

::: callout-note
`step_normalize()` (center + scale) must precede `step_pca()` because
PCA is sensitive to the units of each column.
:::

## Row sampling: `step_downsample()` / `step_upsample()`

When class imbalance is severe (e.g., a 5% fraud rate), the model may
learn to always predict "not fraud." Subsampling at the recipe level
fixes this.

```{r downsample-example}
#| eval: false
# Requires: library(themis)
library(themis)

imbalanced_recipe <-
  recipe(Churn ~ ., data = customer_train) %>%
  step_downsample(Churn) # skip = TRUE by default → not applied at predict time
```

::: callout-warning
Subsampling steps default to `skip = TRUE` — they are applied **only**
during `fit()`, never during `predict()`. This is the correct behaviour:
you adjust the training distribution, not the test distribution.
:::

## General transformations: `step_mutate()`

Mirrors `dplyr::mutate()` inside a recipe — useful for ratio features
and other hand-crafted signals.

```{r step-mutate-example}
ratio_recipe <-
  recipe(Sale_Price ~ ., data = ames_train) %>%
  step_mutate(
    bed_bath_ratio = Bedroom_AbvGr / (Full_Bath + Half_Bath + 0.01),
    house_age = 2024 - Year_Built
  )

# Peek at new columns after baking
ratio_recipe %>%
  prep() %>%
  bake(new_data = ames_train %>% slice(1:4)) %>%
  select(bed_bath_ratio, house_age)
```

::: callout-warning
## Leakage risk with `step_mutate()`

Avoid statistics that depend on the full dataset inside `step_mutate()`.
`x = w > mean(w)` uses `mean(w)` of **new** data at predict time — not
the training mean. Use `step_normalize()` or manual constants instead.
:::

