## Exercise 2 — Adding Normalization Before PCA

The chapter mentions PCA requires predictors to be on the same scale.

a.  Build a recipe that uses `step_normalize()` followed by `step_pca()`
    on all `_SF` and `Gr_Liv` columns. Use `num_comp = 3`.
b.  Use `prep() %>% bake(new_data = NULL)` to inspect the resulting
    training data. What are the names of the PCA columns?
c.  What percentage of variance is explained by each component? Use
    `tidy(prepped_recipe, number = <pca_step_number>)` with
    `type = "variance"`.

```{r ex2-solution}
#| code-fold: true
#| code-summary: "Show solution"
#| eval: false
#| echo: false
pca_rec <-
  recipe(
    Sale_Price ~ Neighborhood +
      Gr_Liv_Area +
      Year_Built +
      Bldg_Type +
      Total_Bsmt_SF +
      First_Flr_SF,
    data = ames_train
  ) %>%
  step_log(Gr_Liv_Area, base = 10) %>%
  step_other(Neighborhood, threshold = 0.01) %>%
  step_normalize(matches("(SF$)|(Gr_Liv)"), id = "norm_step") %>%
  step_pca(matches("(SF$)|(Gr_Liv)"), num_comp = 3, id = "pca_step") %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors())

prepped_pca <- prep(pca_rec)

# b) PCA column names
bake(prepped_pca, new_data = NULL) %>%
  select(starts_with("PC")) %>%
  names()

# c) Variance explained
tidy(prepped_pca, id = "pca_step", type = "variance") %>%
  filter(terms == "percent variance") %>%
  select(component, value)
```

