## Exercise 5 — Debug a Broken Recipe

The following recipe has **three deliberate mistakes**. Identify each
mistake, explain why it is wrong, and provide a corrected version.

```{r ex5-broken}
#| eval: false
broken_recipe <-
  recipe(
    Sale_Price ~ Neighborhood + Gr_Liv_Area + Year_Built + Bldg_Type,
    data = ames_train
  ) %>%
  # Mistake 1
  step_log(Sale_Price, base = 10) %>%
  # Mistake 2
  step_interact(~ Gr_Liv_Area:Bldg_Type) %>%
  # Mistake 3
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  step_other(Neighborhood, threshold = 0.01)
```

```{r ex5-solution}
#| code-fold: true
#| code-summary: "Show solution"
#| echo: false
# Mistake 1: step_log(Sale_Price) — transforming the outcome inside the recipe.
#   This will fail at predict() time because Sale_Price won't exist in new data.
#   Fix: transform Sale_Price in the data frame BEFORE creating the recipe.

# Mistake 2: step_interact(~ Gr_Liv_Area:Bldg_Type) — using a raw factor column
#   in step_interact() before step_dummy() has run. The factor hasn't been encoded
#   yet, which produces unexpected/wrong interaction columns.
#   Fix: move step_interact() AFTER step_dummy().

# Mistake 3: step_dummy() before step_other() — rare Neighborhood levels get
#   their own dummy columns before being pooled. This means the "other" pool
#   is formed from already-dummy-encoded data, which is wrong.
#   Fix: step_other() must come BEFORE step_dummy().

corrected_recipe <-
  recipe(
    Sale_Price ~ Neighborhood + Gr_Liv_Area + Year_Built + Bldg_Type,
    data = ames_train
  ) %>%
  step_log(Gr_Liv_Area, base = 10) %>% # fix 1: log the predictor, not outcome
  step_other(Neighborhood, threshold = 0.01) %>% # fix 3: pool BEFORE dummies
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% # fix 3: dummies after pooling
  step_interact(~ Gr_Liv_Area:starts_with("Bldg_Type_")) # fix 2: interact AFTER dummies

corrected_recipe
```

